[]{#003.html}


## []{#003.html_Tol}**[`<st c="21">`{=html} TOLSTOY AND THE CREATION OF`</st>`{=html}]{.small}*`<st c="49">`{=html} A Calendar of Wisdom`</st>`{=html}*** ![Image](ops/images/img01_1-5.jpg)

`<st c="70">`{=html} PETER SEKIRIN`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="84">`{=html} This was Leo Tolstoy's last major work. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="125">`{=html}With it, he fulfilled a dream he had nourished for almost fifteen years, that of "collecting the wisdom of the centuries in one book" meant for a general audience. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="289">`{=html}Tolstoy put a huge amount of effort into its creation, preparing three revised editions between 1904 and
1910. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="400">`{=html}It was his own favorite
everyday reading, a book he would turn to regularly for the rest of his life.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="501">`{=html} The original idea for this work appeared to come to Tolstoy in the mid-1880s. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="580">`{=html}His first recorded expression of the concept of `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="628">`{=html}A Calendar of Wisdom`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="648">`{=html} ---"A wise thought for every day of the year, from the greatest philosophers of all times and all people"---came in 1884. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="767">`{=html}He wrote in his diary on March 15 of that year: "I have to create a circle of reading for myself: Epictetus, Marcus Aurelius, Lao-Tzu, Buddha, Pascal, The New Testament. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="937">`{=html}This is also necessary for all people." In 1885, he wrote in a letter to his assistant, Mr. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="1029">`{=html}Chertkov: "I know that it gives one great inner force, calmness, and happiness to communicate with such great thinkers as Socrates, Epictetus, Arnold, Parker.... `</st>`{=html}`<st c="1189">`{=html}They tell us about what is most important`</st>`{=html}[]{#003.html_page_6}`<st c="1230">`{=html} for humanity, about the meaning of life and about virtue.... `</st>`{=html}`<st c="1290">`{=html}I would like to create a book ... in which I could tell a person about his life, and about the Good Way of Life."`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="1401">`{=html} The process of collecting these thoughts took over fifteen years. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="1468">`{=html}Tolstoy began writing between December 1902 and January 1903. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="1530">`{=html}Then in his late seventies, he had fallen seriously ill; while meditating about the meaning of life and death, he was inspired to begin compiling what he then called `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="1696">`{=html}A Wise Thought for Every Day`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="1724">`{=html}. When he finally sent the book to his publisher, Tolstoy wrote in his diary: "I felt that I have been elevated to great spiritual and moral heights by communication with the best and wisest people whose books I read and whose thoughts I selected for my `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="1978">`{=html}Circle of Reading`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="1995">`{=html}." He would often return in his diary to meditate upon this book, repeating variants of "What can be more precious than to communicate every day with the wisest men of the world?" Tolstoy carefully selected the contributors to this volume, "among the very best writers," as he repeated to his colleagues and friends. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="2312">`{=html}They represented a wide variety of philosophical views, cultural backgrounds, and historical periods: "It will be a big surprise to the readers," Tolstoy wrote, "that together with Kant and other famous thinkers, they will find in my book thoughts by Lucy Malory, an unknown journalist from the United States, from Oregon." The first edition appeared in 1904 under the title `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="2687">`{=html}Thoughts of Wise Men`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="2707">`{=html}. It saw three editions during Tolstoy's lifetime, between 1904 and 1910, each published with a different subtitle: `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="2823">`{=html}The Way of Life, Circle of Reading,`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="2858">`{=html} and `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="2863">`{=html}A Wise Thought for Every Day`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="2891">`{=html}.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="2892">`{=html} Between 1904 and 1907, Tolstoy worked on the enlarged and completely revised second edition, from which this, its first English translation, is drawn. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3044">`{=html}In mid-August 1905 he wrote the introduction that follows and noted in his diary: "I have revised and enlarged my `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="3158">`{=html}Calendar,`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="3167">`{=html} now it is twice as big. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3192">`{=html}For two months I did not read`</st>`{=html}[]{#003.html_page_7}`<st c="3221">`{=html} anything else, neither newspapers nor magazines, and I felt so good.... `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3292">`{=html}I became more and more astonished by the ignorance, and especially by the cultural, moral ignorance of our society.... `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3409">`{=html}All our education should be directed to the accumulation of the cultural heritage of our ancestors, the best thinkers of the world."`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="3541">`{=html} The major difference between the first edition (`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="3590">`{=html} Thoughts of Wise Men`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="3611">`{=html} ) and the second (`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="3630">`{=html} A Calendar of Wisdom`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="3651">`{=html} ) was that Tolstoy now grouped the thoughts according to topics for a certain day, week, and month. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3752">`{=html}He wrote on June 3, 1904, in his diary: "I am busy with the `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="3812">`{=html}Circle of Reading`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="3829">`{=html}.... `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3832">`{=html}I cannot do anything else.... `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3860">`{=html}I have selected thoughts and grouped them into the following major topics: God, Intellect, Law, Love, Divine Nature of Mankind, Faith, Temptations, Word, Self-Sacrifice, Eternity, Good, Kindness, Unification of People (with God), Prayer, Freedom, Perfection, Work, etc." Tolstoy added about eight hundred of his own thoughts, written during his many years of meditation, or taken from previous diary entries. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="4269">`{=html}He generally started each day with an opening thought of his own, added quotes by other sources, and finished each day with a closing thought of his own.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="4422">`{=html} Additionally, he wrote a short story, or vignette, three to ten pages in length for the end of every week. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="4530">`{=html}Each story corresponded to that week's moral, philosophical, or religious topic; he prepared fifty-two stories in all and called them `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="4664">`{=html}The Sunday Reading Stories`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="4690">`{=html}. The majority of these fifty-two stories were written by Tolstoy especially for this work; the rest were selected and adapted from writings by Plato, Buddha, Dostoevski, Pascal, Leskov, Chekhov, and others. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="4898">`{=html}Tolstoy's prose style in these `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="4929">`{=html}Sunday Reading Stories`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="4951">`{=html} is very different from the sophistication of his earlier novels. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="5017">`{=html}These stories, which were later greatly admired by Pasternak and Solzhenitsyn, were written in a clear, simple, almost primitive language,`</st>`{=html}[]{#003.html_page_8}`<st c="5155">`{=html} designed, as they were, for a wide and general audience. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="5213">`{=html}In them, Tolstoy combined simplicity of form and philosophical depth. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="5283">`{=html}Because these stories did not appear in all editions, and because they are as a whole quite long, they do not appear in this edition.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="5416">`{=html} On December 21, 1904, after reading the galley proofs of the second edition called `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="5500">`{=html}The Calendar: The Circle of Reading for Every Day,`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="5550">`{=html} Tolstoy wrote in his diary: "During this last day I have descended from the spiritual and moral heights where I was all this time when I communicated with the best and wisest thinkers of the world when I created my `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="5766">`{=html}Circle of Reading."`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="5785">`{=html} This title was changed in the second revised edition, published in 1905-1907, to `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="5867">`{=html}Wise Thoughts by Many Writers on Truth, Life, and Behavior Collected and Arranged for Every Day of the Year by Leo Tolstoy`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="5989">`{=html}. From its first publication, the book was always present on Tolstoy's desk; it became his favorite book during the last five years of his life. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="6134">`{=html}Every day, from 1905 to 1910, he read thoughts presented in the book for the corresponding day of the year, and he recommended the same habit to all his friends. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="6296">`{=html}On May 16, 1908, he wrote to a man named Gusev: "I cannot understand how some people can live without communicating with the wisest people who ever lived on Earth? `</st>`{=html}`<st c="6460">`{=html}... I feel very happy every day, because I read this book."`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="6517">`{=html} Tolstoy prepared a third revised, shortened, and simplified edition which appeared in print under the new title `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="6630">`{=html}The Way of Life`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="6645">`{=html} in 1910, the last year of his life. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="6682">`{=html}He wished to make the book easily comprehensible for even the simplest and least educated people---peasants and children. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="6802">`{=html}Most probably, Tolstoy compared `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="6834">`{=html}A Calendar of Wisdom`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="6854">`{=html} to `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="6858">`{=html}War and Peace`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="6871">`{=html} when he wrote that "To create a book for the masses, for millions of people ... is incomparably more important and fruitful than to compose a novel of the kind which diverts some members of the wealthy classes for a short time, and then is forever forgotten. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="7129">`{=html}The region of`</st>`{=html}[]{#003.html_page_9}`<st c="7142">`{=html} this art of the simplest, most widely accessible feeling is enormous, and it is as yet almost untouched." Other editions appeared in Odessa and St. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="7291">`{=html}Petersburg in 1911-1912. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="7316">`{=html}A German critical edition (translated by E. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="7360">`{=html}Schmidt and A. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="7375">`{=html}Schkarvan, Dresden: Karl Reissner, 1907) included the sources of his numerous quotes.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="7460">`{=html} An edition of `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="7475">`{=html}A Calendar of Wisdom`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="7495">`{=html} was published in Russia in 1912, but after the Russian Revolution publication was forbidden under the Soviet regime, because of the book's spiritual orientation and its numerous religious quotes. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="7692">`{=html}When it was again published in Russia, in 1995, after the recent democratic reforms, it enjoyed tremendous success, selling over 300,000 copies.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="7836">`{=html} It has never before been translated into English. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="7887">`{=html}The first English translation of `</st>`{=html}*`<st c="7920">`{=html}A Calendar of Wisdom`</st>`{=html}*`<st c="7940">`{=html} will be a real discovery for the English-speaking reader. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="7999">`{=html}Created by one of the world's greatest novelists and thinkers to represent the very best of the world's spiritual heritage, it draws on the greatest works of religion, philosophy, and literature the world has yet seen. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="8218">`{=html}It belongs among the very best creations of human genius, a work which will serve its readers as a practical spiritual guide on how to live in peace with oneself and how to live a life filled with kindness, satisfaction, and happiness. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="8454">`{=html}Tolstoy's original goal was the delivery of wisdom to the widest possible number of people, "to entertain millions of readers." This aim remains as compelling now, in this time of increasing spiritual need, as it was then.`</st>`{=html}[]{#003.html_page_10}

::: {#003.html_charCountTotal value="8677"} :::

[]{#004.html}


## []{#004.html_Intro}`<st c="21">`{=html} INTRODUCTION`</st>`{=html} ![Image](ops/images/img01_1-5.jpg)

`<st c="34">`{=html} BY LEO TOLSTOY`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="49">`{=html} I took the thoughts collected here from a very large number of works and collections. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="136">`{=html}I indicated the author of each thought beneath it, though I did not mark the exact source or book title or work from which I took it. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="270">`{=html}In some cases, I translated these thoughts not directly from their original sources, but from a translation from the languages in which they became known to me, so sometimes my translations might not be completely identical to the originals. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="512">`{=html}When I translated thoughts by German, French, or Italian thinkers, I did not strictly follow the original, usually making it shorter and easier to understand, and omitting some words. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="696">`{=html}Readers might tell me that a quote is not then Pascal or Rousseau, but my own work, but I think that there is nothing wrong in conveying their thoughts in a modified form. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="868">`{=html}Therefore, if someone desires to translate this book into other languages, I would like to advise them not to look for the original quotes from the English poet Coleridge, say, or the German philosopher Kant, or the French writer Rousseau, but to translate directly from my writing. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="1151">`{=html}Another reason some of these thoughts may not correspond to the originals is at times I took a thought from a lengthy and convoluted argument, and I had to change some words and phrases for`</st>`{=html}[]{#004.html_page_11}`<st c="1340">`{=html} clarity and unity of expression. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="1374">`{=html}In some cases I even express the thought entirely in my own words. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="1441">`{=html}I did this because the purpose of my book is not to give exact, word-for-word translations of thoughts created by other authors, but to use the great and fruitful intellectual heritage created by different writers to present for a wide reading audience an easily accessible, everyday circle of reading which will arouse their best thoughts and feelings.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="1794">`{=html} I hope that the readers of this book may experience the same benevolent and elevating feeling which I have experienced when I was working on its creation, and which I experience again and again, when I reread it every day, working on the enlargement and improvement of the previous edition.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="2085">`{=html} ---LEO TOLSTOY, March 1908`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="2110">`{=html} Note to Reader: In all of the book's original Russian-language editions, Tolstoy highlighted on each page the one quote that most succinctly expressed the day's theme. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="2279">`{=html}These quotes have been italicized in this edition.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="2329">`{=html} ---PETER SEKIRIN`</st>`{=html}

[]{#004.html_page_12}

::: {#004.html_charCountTotal value="2345"} :::

[]{#005.html}


## []{#005.html_Ch01}`<st c="21">`{=html} `</st>`{=html}


### ***`<st c="22">`{=html}January 1`</st>`{=html}*** {#005.html_january1}

![Image](ops/images/img01_013.jpg)

`<st c="31">`{=html} Better to know a few things which are good and necessary than many things which are useless and mediocre.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="137">`{=html} What a great treasure can be hidden in a small, selected library! `</st>`{=html}`<st c="204">`{=html}A company of the wisest and the most deserving people from all the civilized countries of the world, for thousands of years, can make the results of their studies and their wisdom available to us. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="401">`{=html}The thought which they might not even reveal to their best friends is written here in clear words for us, people from another century. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="536">`{=html}Yes, we should be grateful for the best books, for the best spiritual achievements in our lives.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="632">`{=html} ---RALPH WALDO EMERSON`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="653">`{=html} There are too many mediocre books which exist just to entertain your mind. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="729">`{=html}Therefore, read only those books which are accepted without doubt as good.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="803">`{=html} ---LUCIUS ANNAEUS SENECA`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="826">`{=html} Read the best books first, otherwise you'll find you do not have time.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="897">`{=html} ---HENRY DAVID THOREAU`</st>`{=html}

*`<st c="918">`{=html} The difference between real material poison and intellectual poison is that most material poison is disgusting to the taste, but intellectual poison, which takes the form of cheap newspapers or bad books, can unfortunately sometimes be attractive.`</st>`{=html}*[]{#005.html_page_13}


### ***`<st c="1166">`{=html} January 2`</st>`{=html}*** {#005.html_january2}

![Image](ops/images/img01_013.jpg)

`<st c="1176">`{=html} One of the worst prejudices known is held by the majority of the so-called scholars of our time, who claim that a person can live without faith.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="1321">`{=html} Throughout the centuries, in every age, people have wanted to know or at least have a vague idea about the source, the beginning, and the final purpose of their existence. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="1494">`{=html}Religion satisfies this requirement, and makes clear those connections which unite all people as brothers, revealing to them that they have the same source of origin, the same task for their lives, and the same general final goal.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="1724">`{=html} ---GIUSEPPE MAZZINI`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="1742">`{=html} The essential meaning of every religion is to answer the question "Why do I live, and what is my attitude to the limitless world which surrounds me?" There is not a single religion, from the most sophisticated to the most primitive, which does not have as its basis the definition of this attitude of a person to the world.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="2066">`{=html} At the heart of all religions lies a single unifying truth. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="2127">`{=html}Let Persians bear their taovids, Jews wear their caps, Christians bear their cross, Muslims bear their sickle moon, but we have to remember that these are all only outer signs. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="2304">`{=html}The general essence of all religions is love to your neighbor, and that this is requested by Manuf, Zoroaster, Buddha, Moses, Socrates, Jesus, Saint Paul, and Mohammed alike.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="2478">`{=html} ---EWALD FLÃœGEL`</st>`{=html}

*`<st c="2492">`{=html} The life of a person without faith is the life of an animal.`</st>`{=html}*[]{#005.html_page_14}


### ***`<st c="2553">`{=html} January 3`</st>`{=html}*** {#005.html_january3}

![Image](ops/images/img01_013.jpg)

`<st c="2563">`{=html} Those who know the rules of true wisdom are baser than those who love them. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="2640">`{=html}Those who love them are baser than those who follow them.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="2697">`{=html} ---C`</st>`{=html}[`<st c="2700">`{=html} HINESE PROVERB`</st>`{=html}]{.small}

`<st c="2715">`{=html} The most important question to keep before ourselves at all times is this: Do we do the right thing? `</st>`{=html}`<st c="2817">`{=html}During this short period of time which we call our life, do our acts conform to the will of the force that sent us into the world? `</st>`{=html}`<st c="2948">`{=html}Do we do the right thing?`</st>`{=html}

*`<st c="2973">`{=html} When I am in difficult circumstances, I ask God to help me. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3034">`{=html}But it is my duty to serve the Lord, and not His to serve me. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3096">`{=html}As soon as I remember this, my burden becomes lighter.`</st>`{=html}*

`<st c="3150">`{=html} We have to fulfill honestly and irreproachably the work destined for us. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3224">`{=html}It does not matter whether we hope that we will become angels some day, or believe that we have originated from slugs.`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="3342">`{=html} ---JOHN RUSKIN`</st>`{=html}

`<st c="3355">`{=html} Just imagine that the purpose of your life is your happiness only---then life becomes a cruel and senseless thing. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3469">`{=html}You have to embrace what the wisdom of humanity, your intellect, and your heart tell you: that the meaning of life is to serve the force that sent you into the world. `</st>`{=html}`<st c="3636">`{=html}Then life becomes a constant joy.`</st>`{=html}[]{#005.html_page_15}


